df_date = releases.dropna(subset=['released']).copy()

count_year_only  = df_date['released'].str.fullmatch(r'\d{4}',            na=False).sum()
count_year_zero  = df_date['released'].str.fullmatch(r'\d{4}-00-00',      na=False).sum()
count_month_zero = df_date['released'].str.fullmatch(r'\d{4}-00-\d{2}',   na=False).sum()
count_day_zero   = df_date['released'].str.fullmatch(r'\d{4}-\d{2}-00',   na=False).sum()

print(f"Pureyear only   (e.g. '1999')        : {count_year_only}")
print(f"Year-00-00       (e.g. '1997-00-00')  : {count_year_zero}")
print(f"Month-00-DD      (e.g. '1999-00-15')  : {count_month_zero}")
print(f"YYYY-MM-00       (e.g. '1999-07-00')  : {count_day_zero}")

# 4) filter to only valid YYYY-MM-DD strings
mask_valid = df_date['released'].str.fullmatch(r'\d{4}-\d{2}-\d{2}', na=False)
df_date_clean = df_date.loc[mask_valid].copy()

print(f"Rows with full dates (YYYY-MM-DD): {df_date_clean.shape[0]}")

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# 1) Ensure we have a year column
releases['released_dt'] = pd.to_datetime(
    releases['released'],
    format='%Y-%m-%d',
    errors='coerce'
)
releases = releases.dropna(subset=['released_dt'])
releases['year'] = releases['released_dt'].dt.year

# 2) Compute overall artist counts and exclude unwanted entries
artist_counts = releases['artist_name'].value_counts()
exclude = ['Various', 'Unknown Artist', 'No Artist']
filtered_counts = artist_counts[~artist_counts.index.isin(exclude)]

# 3) Top 10 artists all time
top10_all = filtered_counts.head(10)

# 4) Top 10 artists for releases in year >= 2000
post2000 = releases[releases['year'] >= 2000]
artist_counts_2000 = post2000['artist_name'].value_counts()
filtered_counts_2000 = artist_counts_2000[~artist_counts_2000.index.isin(exclude)]
top10_2000 = filtered_counts_2000.head(10)

# 5) Plot side by side with single bar color and larger titles
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(20, 8), sharey=True)

# Common bar color
bar_color = 'steelblue'

# Left: All time
sns.barplot(
    x=top10_all.values,
    y=top10_all.index,
    ax=axes[0],
    color=bar_color
)
axes[0].set_title(
    "Top 10 Artists (All Time)",
    fontsize=20,  # larger title
    fontweight='bold'
)
axes[0].set_xlabel("Number of Releases", fontsize=14)
axes[0].set_ylabel("Artist", fontsize=14)

# Right: From 2000 onwards
sns.barplot(
    x=top10_2000.values,
    y=top10_2000.index,
    ax=axes[1],
    color=bar_color
)
axes[1].set_title(
    "Top 10 Artists (2000Present)",
    fontsize=20,
    fontweight='bold'
)
axes[1].set_xlabel("Number of Releases", fontsize=14)
axes[1].set_ylabel("")  # hide second y-label to reduce clutter

plt.tight_layout()

# 6) Save as SVG
fig.savefig('plots/top10_artists_all_and_post2000.svg', format='svg')

# 7) Show
plt.show()

In[24]:
# B) Area chart: proportions of top 10 genres over time (by year)
#    group and pivot, then normalize to proportions
year_genre_counts = (
    releases
    .groupby(['year','genre'])
    .size()
    .unstack(fill_value=0)
)
year_genre_top = year_genre_counts[top_genres.index]
year_genre_prop = year_genre_top.div(year_genre_top.sum(axis=1), axis=0)

plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
year_genre_prop.plot.area(ax=plt.gca())
plt.title("Top 10 Genres: Proportion of Releases Over Time")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Proportion of Releases")
plt.legend(loc='upper left', ncol=2, fontsize='small')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# 1) Identify the top 10 styles overall
top_styles = releases['style'].value_counts().head(10).index

# 2) Compute annual release counts for those top styles
year_style_counts = (
    releases
    .groupby(['year', 'style'])
    .size()
    .unstack(fill_value=0)
)[top_styles]

# 3) Split into before-2000 and after-2000
before2000 = year_style_counts[year_style_counts.index < 2000]
after2000  = year_style_counts[year_style_counts.index >= 2000]

# 4) Plot side by side with custom ylimits
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16, 6), sharey=False)

# before 2000
for style in top_styles:
    axes[0].plot(before2000.index, before2000[style], label=style)
axes[0].set_title("Top 10 Styles before 2000y")
axes[0].set_xlabel("Year")
axes[0].set_ylabel("Releases")
axes[0].set_ylim(0, 1000)
axes[0].legend(loc='upper left', fontsize='small')

# after 2000
for style in top_styles:
    axes[1].plot(after2000.index, after2000[style], label=style)
axes[1].set_title("Top 10 Styles after 2000y")
axes[1].set_xlabel("Year")
axes[1].set_ylim(0, 10000)
axes[1].legend(loc='upper left', fontsize='small')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# 1) Ensure we have a 'year' column
releases['released_dt'] = pd.to_datetime(
    releases['released'],
    format='%Y-%m-%d',
    errors='coerce'
)
releases = releases.dropna(subset=['released_dt'])
releases['year'] = releases['released_dt'].dt.year

# 2) Identify the top 5 formats overall
top5_formats = releases['format_name'].value_counts().head(5).index

# 3) Build a year  format pivot of counts
year_fmt = (
    releases
    .groupby(['year','format_name'])
    .size()
    .unstack(fill_value=0)
)[top5_formats]

# 4) Plot as line chart
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
for fmt in top5_formats:
    plt.plot(year_fmt.index, year_fmt[fmt], marker='o', label=fmt)
plt.title("Annual Release Counts by Top 5 Formats", fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel("Year", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Number of Releases", fontsize=14)
plt.legend(title="Format", fontsize=12)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('plots/top5_formats_all.svg', format='svg') 
plt.show()

masters['video_duration_list'] = masters['video_duration'].apply(ast.literal_eval)
masters_exp = masters.explode('video_duration_list')

# 3) Robust parser for mixed types
def parse_duration(val):
    """
    val might be:
      - a string "mm:ss"
      - a numeric string "451"
      - an int 451
    We convert all to an integer number of seconds.
    """
    if pd.isna(val):
        return None
    # ensure string for splitting
    text = str(val)
    if ':' in text:
        m, s = text.split(':', 1)
        return int(m)*60 + int(s)
    else:
        return int(float(text))  # handles "451" or 451

masters_exp['duration_sec'] = masters_exp['video_duration_list'].map(parse_duration)

# 4) (Optional) average per master
master_avg = (
    masters_exp
    .groupby('master_id')['duration_sec']
    .mean()
    .reset_index(name='avg_video_duration_sec')
)

# 5) Join back to releases
joined = releases.merge(master_avg, on='master_id', how='inner')

#  3) Join back onto `releases` 
joined = pd.merge(
    releases,
    masters_exp[['master_id','duration_sec']],
    on='master_id',
    how='inner'
)

#  4) Test 1: Trend over time 
# average duration each year
annual = joined.groupby('year')['duration_sec'].mean().reset_index()
slope, intercept, r_val, p_val, stderr = linregress(
    annual['year'], annual['duration_sec']
)
print("Trend Test: video duration vs. year")
print(f"  slope = {slope:.2f} sec/year")
print(f"  R    = {r_val**2:.3f}")
print(f"  p-value = {p_val:.3g}")
print("  ", "Significant trend" if p_val < 0.05 else "No significant trend")

#  5) Test 2: Genre differences 
# group durations by genre (require 30 samples per genre)
genre_groups = []
genre_labels = []
for name, grp in joined.groupby('genre'):
    if len(grp) >= 30:
        genre_groups.append(grp['duration_sec'].values)
        genre_labels.append(name)

# one-way ANOVA
f_stat, p_anova = f_oneway(*genre_groups)
print("\nANOVA across genres:")
print(f"  F = {f_stat:.2f}, p-value = {p_anova:.3g}")
print("  ", "Means differ by genre" if p_anova < 0.05 else "No genre effect")

# KruskalWallis nonparametric
h_stat, p_kruskal = kruskal(*genre_groups)
print("\nKruskalWallis across genres:")
print(f"  H = {h_stat:.2f}, p-value = {p_kruskal:.3g}")
print("  ", "Distributions differ by genre" if p_kruskal < 0.05 else "No genre effect")
